{{Infobox musical artist | name = Victor Wulf | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | genre = [[Sound collage]], [[ambient music|ambient]] | occupation = Musician | married_to = | instrument = | label = [[Cleopatra Records|Cleopatra]] | years_active = 1989–1997 | associated_acts = [[Dilate (musical project)|Dilate]], [[Vampire Rodents]] }}
'''Victor Wulf''' is a Canadian [[keyboard player]] and composer. He is recognized for his solo [[ambient music]] project [[Dilate (musical project)|Dilate]] and as a founding member of [[sound collage]] band [[Vampire Rodents]].
==Biography== Victor Wulf was involved in composing music for television since 1977.<ref name="maven">{{cite web | url=http://soundmaven.com/artist/Dilate/ | title=Artist Page:Dilate | publisher=Sound Maven | accessdate=October 11, 2016}}</ref> In June 1989, Wulf and Vahnke founded [[Vampire Rodents]], a project that incorporated elements of [[industrial rock]] and [[sound collage]].<ref name="rodentint07">{{cite web |first=Gabe |last=Wilkinson |url=http://themindofmicrowaved.blogspot.com/2007/06/vampire-rodentsether-bunny-interview.html |title=Vampire Rodents/Ether Bunny Interview 2007 |publisher=themindofmicrowaved.blogspot.com |date=June 2007 |accessdate=October 11, 2016}}</ref> The duo released three albums: ''[[War Music (Vampire Rodents album)|War Music]]'' (1990), ''[[Premonition (Vampire Rodents album)|Premonition]]'' (1992) and ''[[Lullaby Land (album)|Lullaby Land]]'' (1993). During this time, Wulf was primary influenced by [[Can (band)|Can]], [[Bernard Herrmann]], [[John Zorn]] and [[Big band|big band music]].<ref name="technologyworks91">{{cite journal|first= |last=Chase |url=http://www.msu.edu/~tarjason/TechWorks.htm |title=Interview with Victor Wulf and Anton Rathausen of the Vampire Rodents |journal=Technology Works |date=1991 |issue=12 |accessdate=September 15, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000518193302/http://www.msu.edu/~tarjason/TechWorks.htm |archivedate=May 18, 2000 }}</ref>
Wulf became less involved in the writing process with each album and he decided to leave Vampire Rodents after the release of ''Lullaby Land''. Wulf founded his own [[ambient music]] project [[Dilate (musical project)|Dilate]] in 1995. After being picked up by [[Cleopatra Records]], he released ''[[Cyclos (album)|Cyclos]]'' in early 1996.<ref name="discog">{{cite web | url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p204768|pure_url=yes}} | title=Dilate Discography | work=[[Allmusic]] | accessdate=October 11, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Octagon (Dilate album)|Octagon]]'' was released in 1997.
==Discography== '''Dilate''' * ''[[Cyclos (album)|Cyclos]]'' ([[Cleopatra Records|Cleopatra]], 1996) * ''[[Octagon (Dilate album)|Octagon]]'' (Cleopatra, 1997)
'''Vampire Rodents''' *''[[War Music (Vampire Rodents album)|War Music]]'' (V.R., 1990) *''[[Premonition (Vampire Rodents album)|Premonition]]'' (V.R., 1992) *''[[Lullaby Land (album)|Lullaby Land]]'' ([[Re-Constriction Records|Re-Constriction]], 1993)
